04993nam a22006735i 9780804793209DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2014025471  a97808047932097 a10.1515/97808047932092doi  a(DE-B1597)564506  a(OCoLC)1198930816  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aF2191.R33bT85 2015 4aF2191.R33 7aHIS0240002bisacsh04a305.8009461 aTwinam, Ann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPurchasing Whiteness :bPardos, Mulattos, and the Quest for Social Mobility in the Spanish Indies /cAnn Twinam. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (552 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tOne. Conclusions: -- tTwo. Introductions -- tThree. Interstices -- tFour. Connections -- tFive. Benchmarks -- tSix. Balances -- tSeven. Exceptions -- tEight. Opportunities -- tNine. Dissentions and Discords: 1796-1803 -- tTen. Denouements: 1803-1806 -- tEleven. Recalibrations -- tTwelve. Evolutions -- tThirteen. Retrospectives -- tAppendix A: Archival/Printed References to Whitening Cases -- tAppendix B: Dates of Service, Vacancies, and Experience of Fiscals for Peru and New Spain (Mexico) -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe colonization of Spanish America resulted in the mixing of Natives, Europeans, and Africans and the subsequent creation of a casta system that discriminated against them. Members of mixed races could, however, free themselves from such burdensome restrictions through the purchase of a gracias al sacar-a royal exemption that provided the privileges of Whiteness. For more than a century, the whitening gracias al sacar has fascinated historians. Even while the documents remained elusive, scholars continually mentioned the potential to acquire Whiteness as a provocative marker of the historic differences between Anglo and Latin American treatments of race. Purchasing Whiteness explores the fascinating details of 40 cases of whitening petitions, tracking thousands of pages of ensuing conversations as petitioners, royal officials, and local elites disputed not only whether the state should grant full whiteness to deserving individuals, but whether selective prejudices against the castas should cease. Purchasing Whiteness contextualizes the history of the gracias al sacar within the broader framework of three centuries of mixed race efforts to end discrimination. It identifies those historic variables that structured the potential for mobility as Africans moved from slavery to freedom, mixed with Natives and Whites, and transformed later generations into vassals worthy of royal favor. By examining this history of pardo and mulatto mobility, the author provides striking insight into those uniquely characteristic and deeply embedded pathways through which the Hispanic world negotiated processes of inclusion and exclusion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aRace discriminationxColonieszSpainxHistory. 0aRace discriminationzCaribbean AreaxHistory. 0aRace discriminationzSpainxColoniesxHistory. 0aRacially mixed peoplexColonieszSpainxHistory. 0aRacially mixed peoplexLegal status, laws, etczCaribbean AreaxHistory. 0aRacially mixed peoplexLegal status, laws, etc.zCaribbean AreaxHistory. 0aRacially mixed peoplezSpainxColoniesxHistory. 4aAnglo America. 4acastas. 4acomparison socioracial practice Spanish. 4agracias al sacar. 4ahistory mulatto mobility. 4aprocesses of inclusion and exclusion. 4apurchase of whiteness. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is par